{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 \outlinelevel1 \b \fs32 A Note from the Author\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 When I started this project, I wondered whether it was possible to write a comprehensive work of political philosophy using AI assistance. The answer, I\u8217've discovered, is yes\u8212-but with important caveats.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The AI didn\u8217't write this book. I did. Don\u8217't confuse the painter with the brush. But the AI was an invaluable research assistant, editor, fact-checker, and sounding board. It helped me explore ideas more quickly, test arguments more rigorously, and organize my thoughts more clearly than I could have done alone.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 Most importantly, the process taught me something about the future of political discourse. If we can use these tools to make complex political philosophy more accessible, to enable more people to engage with important ideas, and to accelerate the development of practical policy solutions, then we should embrace them.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 But we must do so thoughtfully. AI is a tool, not an oracle. It can help us think, but it cannot do our thinking for us. It can organize information, but it cannot replace political judgment. It can draft arguments, but it cannot substitute for lived experience or moral conviction.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 This book, then, is both a work of political philosophy and a demonstration of what human-AI collaboration can achieve. I hope it succeeds at both.\par}
{\pard \ql \f0 \sa180 \li0 \fi0 The lemons are already here. Together\u8212-humans and our tools\u8212-we can make something refreshing.\par}
